      # how to win at node.js knockout

      ## ground rules
       * node.js + 48 hours
       * teams of up to 4
       * don't cheat, be cool

      ## why do I care?
       * [prizes], glory
       * try out node.js
       * finally build that idea you've had

      [prizes]: http://2010.nodeknockout.com/prizes

  .slide#slide-1
    :markdown
      # know thy audience

      * we [publish the judges][1]
        * "would they get this?"
        * technology category this year
      * no login, no signup
      * [browser breakdown][2]

      [1]: http://2010.nodeknockout.com/judges
      [2]: http://2010.nodeknockout.com/faq

  .slide#slide-2
    :markdown
      # click click click click click click click

      * cheat the [popular vote][1]
      * be controversial, newsworthy
      * **brain hacking**
        * empathy + delight

      [1]: http://2010.nodeknockout.com/judging

  .slide#slide-3
    h1 plan ahea<sup>d</sup>
    :markdown
      * sketch out everything beforehand
      * familiarize yourself with libs
      * know your tools: git, npm, core api
      * divide and conquer
      * cut scope-able
      * message on bugs, news

  .slide#slide-4
    :markdown
      # there is no I in team

      * work with people you know
      * dream team: 2 designers + 2 developers

  .slide#slide-5
    :markdown
      # frak tests

      * deploy early
      * don't write tests
      * leverage hosted services
      * leverage node.js

  .slide#slide-6
    h1
      a( href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorodango' ) dorodango
      |  for all!
    :markdown
      * spend an entire day polishing
      * 2 designers?
      * smoke & mirrors

  .slide#slide-7
    :markdown
      # yo dude, 'sup?

      * take breaks
        * sketch on paper
        * talk to your team
        * cut the feature (or hack around it)
      * sleep
      * eat

